      "content='{\"step_id\":12,\"analysis_path\":\"general_debugging\",\"reasoning\":\"The \\'ps -m\\' output shows many tasks, but I need to filter for UNINTERRUPTIBLE state. I see one task with [UN] state: PID 81100 (kworker/1:3). However, the main hung task is PID 81115 (rcu_stall_thr) which is in RU (running) state on CPU 0. The soft lockup is due to this task running an infinite delay loop. The evidence from disassembly and memory read confirms the module is intentionally stalling. I have enough information to conclude the root cause. I\\'ll provide a final diagnosis.\",\"knowledge_base_hit\":null,\"action\":null,\"is_conclusive\":true,\"final_diagnosis\":\"Root cause: Third-party kernel module \\'rcu_stall_mod\\' intentionally caused a CPU soft lockup by executing an infinite delay loop. The module\\'s \\'rcu_stall_thread\\' function calls \\'__const_udelay\\' (which internally calls \\'delay_tsc\\') in a loop based on \\'stall_duration_ms\\' set to 70000 ms (0x11170). The disassembly shows a backward jump in \\'delay_tsc\\' (jb to offset +40) creating a tight loop, and \\'rcu_stall_thread\\' has a jmp back to test the duration counter. The watchdog detected CPU#0 stuck for 26s, triggering a kernel panic. Evidence: 1) Backtrace shows RIP at delay_tsc+63. 2) Disassembly of delay_tsc reveals loop structure. 3) Disassembly of rcu_stall_thread shows infinite loop with jmp. 4) Memory read of stall_duration_ms confirms 70000 ms. 5) Dmesg logs indicate module loaded and started stall simulation. This is a deliberate stall simulation by the module, not a kernel bug.\"}' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='74ff1614-a68f-4f88-859f-24a5dfb28734' tool_calls=[] invalid_tool_calls=[]"
