      "content='{\"step_id\":20,\"reasoning\":\"This is raw data and hard to interpret. Given the evidence, I have enough to conclude the root cause. The soft lockup occurred because the \\'rcu_stall_mod\\' kernel module called \\'delay_tsc\\' with an excessively large cycle count (RDI = 0x140196507175), causing the CPU to spin in a delay loop for much longer than intended (70000 ms). The watchdog detected this after 27 seconds and triggered a panic. The bug is in the module\\'s calculation of TSC cycles from milliseconds. The module likely used an incorrect conversion factor or had an integer overflow. This is consistent with the dmesg message about simulating a stall for 70000 ms. Therefore, the final diagnosis is a bug in the third-party \\'rcu_stall_mod\\' module that causes a soft lockup due to an incorrect delay parameter passed to \\'delay_tsc\\'.\",\"action\":null,\"is_conclusive\":true,\"final_diagnosis\":\"Root cause: The kernel panic (soft lockup) was triggered by the \\'rcu_stall_mod\\' kernel module. The module\\'s \\'rcu_stall_thread\\' function called \\'delay_tsc\\' with a cycle count of 0x140196507175 (approximately 1.378e12 cycles), which corresponds to an estimated delay of ~689 seconds on a 2 GHz CPU. This far exceeds the intended 70000 ms (70 seconds) stall simulation advertised in the kernel log. The excessive delay caused CPU 1 to spin in the \\'delay_tsc\\' loop for over 27 seconds, tripping the watchdog soft lockup detector. Evidence: 1) Backtrace shows the crash in \\'delay_tsc\\' called from \\'rcu_stall_thread\\'. 2) Register RDI at crash holds the large cycle count. 3) Kernel log confirms the module loaded and started a 70000 ms stall simulation. 4) The mismatch between intended delay (70s) and actual parameter (~689s) indicates a bug in the module\\'s time-to-TSC conversion logic.\"}' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='d1155f85-c287-4b59-8374-398e12e2821e' tool_calls=[] invalid_tool_calls=[]"
