      "content='{\"step_id\":9,\"reasoning\":\"The \\'mod\\' output shows rcu_stall_mod is loaded but with \\'(not loaded) [CONFIG_KALLSYMS]\\', which might indicate the symbols are not fully loaded despite my earlier command. However, the module is present. The memory read at RIP shows raw bytes, but I need to disassemble them to understand the instruction. Since the disassembly commands are not working well, I should use \\'dis -r\\' on the memory range around RIP to see the assembly. Let\\'s disassemble from 0xffffffffb9cf022f to 0xffffffffb9cf02af (about 128 bytes) to capture the loop. Also, I need to understand the context: the dmesg says the module started a stall simulation for 70000 ms, and the soft lockup occurred after 27s. This suggests the module is intentionally causing a delay, possibly via a busy-wait loop in delay_tsc. I should examine the registers from the backtrace to see the arguments passed to delay_tsc. In x86_64, the first argument is in RDI. From the backtrace, RDI is 0x0000140196507175. This might be a delay value. Let\\'s check the source of delay_tsc by looking at the kernel source location: /usr/src/debug/kernel-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7/linux-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7.x86_64/arch/x86/lib/delay.c. I can use \\'dis -s\\' to see source code if available. First, let\\'s disassemble with source for delay_tsc.\",\"action\":{\"command_name\":\"dis\",\"arguments\":[\"-s\",\"delay_tsc\"]},\"is_conclusive\":false,\"final_diagnosis\":null}' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='34dd44e9-6a0a-4644-bfe3-d1cd5441c864' tool_calls=[{'name': 'dis', 'args': {'command': '-s delay_tsc'}, 'id': 'call_9', 'type': 'tool_call'}] invalid_tool_calls=[]",
      "content='crash> dis -s delay_tsc\\nFILE: arch/x86/lib/delay.c\\nLINE: 64\\n\\n  59\\t\\t);\\n  60\\t}\\n  61\\t\\n  62\\t/* TSC based delay: */\\n  63\\tstatic void delay_tsc(u64 cycles)\\n* 64\\t{\\n  65\\t\\tu64 bclock, now;\\n  66\\t\\tint cpu;\\n  67\\t\\n  68\\t\\tpreempt_disable();\\n  69\\t\\tcpu = smp_processor_id();\\n  70\\t\\tbclock = rdtsc_ordered();\\n  71\\t\\tfor (;;) {\\n  72\\t\\t\\tnow = rdtsc_ordered();\\n  73\\t\\t\\tif ((now - bclock) >= cycles)\\n  74\\t\\t\\t\\tbreak;\\n  75\\t\\n  76\\t\\t\\t/* Allow RT tasks to run */\\n  77\\t\\t\\tpreempt_enable();\\n  78\\t\\t\\trep_nop();\\n  79\\t\\t\\tpreempt_disable();\\n  80\\t\\n  81\\t\\t\\t/*\\n  82\\t\\t\\t * It is possible that we moved to another CPU, and\\n  83\\t\\t\\t * since TSC\\'s are per-cpu we need to calculate\\n  84\\t\\t\\t * that. The delay must guarantee that we wait \"at\\n  85\\t\\t\\t * least\" the amount of time. Being moved to another\\n  86\\t\\t\\t * CPU could make the wait longer but we just need to\\n  87\\t\\t\\t * make sure we waited long enough. Rebalance the\\n  88\\t\\t\\t * counter for this CPU.\\n  89\\t\\t\\t */\\n  90\\t\\t\\tif (unlikely(cpu != smp_processor_id())) {\\n  91\\t\\t\\t\\tcycles -= (now - bclock);\\n  92\\t\\t\\t\\tcpu = smp_processor_id();\\n  93\\t\\t\\t\\tbclock = rdtsc_ordered();\\n  94\\t\\t\\t}\\n  95\\t\\t}\\n  96\\t\\tpreempt_enable();\\n  97\\t}' id='30f5d6e8-2257-41fb-9c9f-e0a9c5f80361' tool_call_id='call_9'",
      "content='{\"step_id\":10,\"reasoning\":\"Excellent! Now I have the source code for delay_tsc. It\\'s a function that delays for a given number of TSC cycles. The function has an infinite loop (for (;;)) that breaks when (now - bclock) >= cycles. The RIP is at line 90: \\'if (unlikely(cpu != smp_processor_id()))\\', which corresponds to the instruction at delay_tsc+63 (mov %gs:0x46342796(%rip),%esi) as seen earlier. This instruction is loading the current CPU ID. The crash occurred because the CPU is stuck in this loop, meaning the condition (now - bclock) >= cycles is never met. This indicates that the \\'cycles\\' argument is too large or the TSC isn\\'t advancing (e.g., due to virtualization or bug). From the backtrace, RDI (first argument) is 0x0000140196507175, which is a huge value (about 1.4e19). This is likely the cycles parameter causing a very long delay. The dmesg says the module started a stall simulation for 70000 ms, so it probably called delay_tsc with a cycles value corresponding to 70 seconds. However, the soft lockup was detected after 27s, so the loop is still ongoing. To confirm, I need to see how rcu_stall_thread calls delay_tsc. Let\\'s examine the stack frame of rcu_stall_thread to get the arguments. Use \\'bt -f\\' to dump the stack for the current task (PID 10664).\",\"action\":{\"command_name\":\"bt\",\"arguments\":[\"-f\"]},\"is_conclusive\":false,\"final_diagnosis\":null}' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='193f11ee-a791-441d-89b8-4b6c2d5a1604' tool_calls=[{'name': 'bt', 'args': {'command': '-f'}, 'id': 'call_10', 'type': 'tool_call'}] invalid_tool_calls=[]",
