      "content='{\"step_id\":5,\"reasoning\":\"I made an error: bt -f expects a PID or task address, not a stack pointer. The backtrace shows the task address is ffff8ab9ab539cc0 (from R15 in frame #8). I should use that. Alternatively, I can examine the stack memory directly using rd starting from RSP ffff9a4cc5873eb0 to see the local variables. Since the loop counter is at -0x40(%rbp), and RBP is ffff9a4cc5873f10 (from frame #8), I can compute the address: RBP - 0x40 = ffff9a4cc5873f10 - 0x40 = ffff9a4cc5873ed0. I\\'ll read that address to see the current loop counter value.\",\"action\":{\"command_name\":\"rd\",\"arguments\":[\"ffff9a4cc5873ed0\"]},\"is_conclusive\":false,\"final_diagnosis\":null}' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='fee33194-8e63-4888-af6a-6d97baf45cd9' tool_calls=[{'name': 'rd', 'args': {'command': 'ffff9a4cc5873ed0'}, 'id': 'call_5', 'type': 'tool_call'}] invalid_tool_calls=[]",
      "content='crash> rd ffff9a4cc5873ed0\\nffff9a4cc5873ed0:  000000000000b30d                    ........' id='3f4a8120-a337-4764-b28f-6f71788a41ec' tool_call_id='call_5'",
      "content='{\"step_id\":6,\"reasoning\":\"The loop counter value is 0xb30d, which is 45837 in decimal. This means the loop has executed approximately 70000 - 45837 = 24163 iterations so far, indicating it\\'s still in progress and not stuck in an infinite loop. The soft lockup occurred because the delay is too long (70000 ms) and the watchdog timeout (default 20 seconds) was exceeded. The root cause is confirmed: the module rcu_stall_mod is designed to simulate an RCU stall by delaying for 70000 ms, which triggers a soft lockup. This is intentional behavior from the module, but it caused a kernel panic due to the watchdog. I should also check if there are any other issues, but the evidence is clear. I\\'ll conclude the diagnosis.\",\"action\":null,\"is_conclusive\":true,\"final_diagnosis\":\"Root cause: The kernel panic was caused by a soft lockup due to a third-party kernel module \\'rcu_stall_mod\\' intentionally simulating an RCU stall. The module\\'s function rcu_stall_thread contains a loop that iterates stall_duration_ms times (70000), each iteration calling __const_udelay (which internally calls delay_tsc). This results in a CPU stall exceeding the watchdog timeout (27 seconds), triggering the soft lockup detection and panic.\\\\n\\\\nEvidence:\\\\n1. Backtrace shows the hung task is \\'rcu_stall_thr\\' stuck in delay_tsc+63, called from rcu_stall_thread in rcu_stall_mod.\\\\n2. Dmesg indicates the module started a stall simulation for 70000 ms.\\\\n3. Disassembly of rcu_stall_thread reveals a loop that decrements a counter from stall_duration_ms and calls __const_udelay until zero.\\\\n4. The global variable stall_duration_ms at 0xffffffffc0d29058 contains 0x11170 (70000 decimal).\\\\n5. The current loop counter at crash time is 0xb30d (45837 decimal), showing the loop was still executing, not infinite.\\\\n\\\\nThis is a deliberate module behavior causing a watchdog violation, leading to kernel panic.\"}' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='1