      "content='{\"step_id\":8,\"reasoning\":\"Now I understand the delay_tsc function. It reads the TSC (Time Stamp Counter) and loops until the elapsed TSC cycles exceed the requested delay (passed in RDI). The crash RIP is at delay_tsc+63, which is \\'mov %gs:0x46342796(%rip),%esi\\' \u2013 this loads a per-CPU variable (likely \\'loops_per_jiffy\\' or similar). The next instruction compares it with r8d. If they are not equal, it jumps to delay_tsc+115 for adjustment. The loop condition is at delay_tsc+96: \\'cmp %r9,%rdx; jb 0xffffffffb9cf0218\\'. This means if the elapsed TSC cycles (rdx) are less than the requested delay (r9), it jumps back to delay_tsc+40 (which includes a pause and increments). So the CPU is stuck in this loop because the TSC is not advancing or the comparison is failing. The soft lockup indicates the loop is taking too long. Possible causes: 1) The TSC is frozen or broken (unlikely in VM). 2) The requested delay value (in r9) is extremely large, causing a long delay. From the backtrace, RDI (first argument to delay_tsc) is 0x0000140196507175? Wait, the backtrace shows RDI: 0000140196507175. But delay_tsc expects the delay in RDI (from the calling convention). However, in the disassembly of rcu_stall_thread, the argument to __const_udelay is 0x418958, not this large value. Let\\'s check the register values at crash: RDI is 0x0000140196507175, which is huge (~1.4e13). That suggests the argument passed to delay_tsc is incorrect, causing an enormous delay. This could be due to a bug in __const_udelay or in the calculation. I need to see what __const_udelay does. Let\\'s disassemble __const_udelay.\",\"action\":{\"command_name\":\"dis\",\"arguments\":[\"-l\",\"__const_udelay\",\"20\"]},\"is_conclusive\":false,\"final_diagnosis\":null}' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='dc43b0a3-d22a-48af-aed4-1205af460bdd' tool_calls=[{'name': 'dis', 'args': {'command': '-l __const_udelay 20'}, 'id': 'call_8', 'type': 'tool_call'}] invalid_tool_calls=[]",
      "content='crash> dis -l __const_udelay 20\\n/usr/src/debug/kernel-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7/linux-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7.x86_64/arch/x86/lib/delay.c: 208\\n0xffffffffb9cf0160 <__const_udelay>:\\tnopl   0x0(%rax,%rax,1) [FTRACE NOP]\\n/usr/src/debug/kernel-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7/linux-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7.x86_64/arch/x86/lib/delay.c: 209\\n0xffffffffb9cf0165 <__const_udelay+5>:\\tmov    %gs:0x463298c3(%rip),%rdx        # 0x19a30\\n0xffffffffb9cf016d <__const_udelay+13>:\\ttest   %rdx,%rdx\\n0xffffffffb9cf0170 <__const_udelay+16>:\\tcmove  0x1729ed8(%rip),%rdx        # 0xffffffffbb41a050 <loops_per_jiffy>\\n/usr/src/debug/kernel-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7/linux-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7.x86_64/arch/x86/lib/delay.c: 212\\n0xffffffffb9cf0178 <__const_udelay+24>:\\tlea    0x0(,%rdi,4),%rax\\n/usr/src/debug/kernel-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7/linux-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7.x86_64/arch/x86/lib/delay.c: 213\\n0xffffffffb9cf0180 <__const_udelay+32>:\\timul   $0xfa,%rdx,%rdx\\n0xffffffffb9cf0187 <__const_udelay+39>:\\tmul    %edx\\n/usr/src/debug/kernel-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7/linux-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7.x86_64/arch/x86/lib/delay.c: 203\\n0xffffffffb9cf0189 <__const_udelay+41>:\\tmov    0x1107bd8(%rip),%rax        # 0xffffffffbadf7d68 <delay_fn>\\n/usr/src/debug/kernel-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7/linux-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7.x86_64/arch/x86/lib/delay.c: 217\\n0xffffffffb9cf0190 <__const_udelay+48>:\\tlea    0x1(%rdx),%rdi\\n/usr/src/debug/kernel-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7/linux-5.14.0-611.9.1.el9_7.x86_64/arch/x86/lib/delay.c: 203\\n0xffffffffb9cf0194 <__const_udelay+52>:\\tjmp    0xffffffffba350560 <__x86_indirect_its_thunk_array>\\n0xffffffffb9cf0199 <__const_udelay+57>:\\tint3\\n0xffffffffb9cf019a <__const_udelay+58>:\\tnopw   0x0(%rax,%rax,1)\\n0xffffffffb9cf01a0 <__pfx___udelay>:\\tnop\\n0xffffffffb9cf01a1 <__pfx___udelay+1>:\\tnop\\n0xffffffffb9cf01a2 <__pfx___udelay+2>:\\tnop\\n0xffffffffb9cf01a3 <__pfx___udelay+3>:\\tnop\\n0xffffffffb9cf01a4 <__pfx___udelay+4>:\\tnop\\n0xffffffffb9cf01a5 <__pfx___udelay+5>:\\tno